<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:department>Hebrew and Jewish Studies</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/0D110F68-AA76-42A2-9B22-25AF1665E01D"><gtr:id>0D110F68-AA76-42A2-9B22-25AF1665E01D</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Sacha</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Stern</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=AH%2FF009518%2F1"><gtr:id>8F4BF9B9-D93D-4565-9F54-CB71BEEE1A8D</gtr:id><gtr:title>Medieval monographs on the Jewish calendar</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>AH/F009518/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>A number of monographs describing the Jewish calendar, its origins, and how weeks, months, and years are reckoned in Jewish tradition were written by various Hebrew authors in the first half of the 12th century CE. These works have largely been ignored in modern scholarship; yet calendars are central to social life, and the large number of manuscripts that have survived of these works demonstrates the importance they must have held in Jewish medieval culture.\n\nIn this project we propose to examine the calendar monographs of Jacob b.Shimshon, Abraham b.Hiyya, and Abraham ibn Ezra (all early 12th cent.) and produce modern editions with critical apparatus, translation, introduction, and commentary. Such editions have never yet been produced. Our project will involve first compilation, then textual and codicological analysis, of all the manuscripts extant; elucidation of the calendrical, astronomical, and mathematical contents of the works; and source and literary criticism. A comparison of these works will be carried out, and consideration will be taken of their broader context including other relevant works by the same authors, Islamic and Chistian calendars and calendar monographs from the medieval period, controversies on the calendar between Rabbanites (who authored our monographs on the Jewish calendar) and Karaites, and medieval astronomy (which forms an essential component of these works).</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2013-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/1291772D-DFCE-493A-AEE7-24F7EEAFE0E9"><gtr:id>1291772D-DFCE-493A-AEE7-24F7EEAFE0E9</gtr:id><gtr:name>AHRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>732242</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Live talks at University of Oxford Chabad Society; subsequently put online at chabad.org</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Regional</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>3B9762DB-0D4C-49C9-B5D0-E9302798AE71</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The events were well attended and open to the broad community; they generated a lot of interest. The talks were subsequently put online (see one of the URLs below).</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>5899a551798f96.89648687</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.chabad.org/multimedia/media_cdo/aid/3521528/jewish/Before-the-Ghettos-Jewish-Intellectual-Life-in-Medieval-Italy.htm</gtr:url><gtr:year>2015,2016</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Research undertaken in this project on medieval calendars and Hebrew manuscripts has been disseminated to the broader public at public talks given to the Oxford Chabad Society, which are also accessible online, and through a contribution to the British Library website.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2015</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>33ABA9C2-1D2D-477B-BC38-F2DC029F4CD8</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>5899a2ed64b479.08482310</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Education,Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Two medieval Hebrew books on the subject of the Jewish calendar (by Abraham bar Hiyya and by Jacob bar Samson, both writing in 1123) have been critically edited on the basis of extant manuscripts, translated, and annotated with a commentary. They are currently being edited, and will soon be submitted for publication.
These works are the earliest complete books that were written in Hebrew on the fixed rabbinic calendar, which was instituted in the early Middle Ages and is still in use today. They explain the meaning of 'days', 'months', and 'years', the origins and scientific foundations of the Jewish calendar (based on medieval astronomy and mathematics), how this calendar works, and how it compares to other medieval calendars, e.g. Christian and Islamic.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>This project makes accessible to the research community two major medieval Hebrew scientific works. They will be of use not only to students and researchers of the Jewish calendar and its history, but also more generally to students and researchers of Jewish medieval science, and to students and researchers of medieval calendar and computistical sciences (Christian in particular). They will be studied as primary sources for the history of medieval Jewish science and of medieval scientific literature in Hebrew.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>E4DF4603-C824-4B08-9BAA-9203AF230D8B</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5898b5d6723090.44338504</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Education,Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>9A138F10-1646-4317-882C-8ED750ED1E28</gtr:id><gtr:title>Time, Astronomy, and Calendars in the Jewish Tradition</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/a67fa7857221a85401a57ebd8437d80f"><gtr:id>a67fa7857221a85401a57ebd8437d80f</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Wartenberg I</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2013-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9789004259669</gtr:isbn><gtr:issn>Stern S</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>r_934248311391cf2872</gtr